Reason carefully through the fundamental tension in infrastructure-as-code generation tools between prescriptive best practices and contextual flexibility. A tool that generates Kubernetes manifests, Terraform modules, or Helm charts with opinionated security defaults (runAsNonRoot: true, resource limits always set, read-only root filesystem) will be wrong for some legitimate use cases. A tool that generates permissive defaults is usable but produces insecure infrastructure by default.

Consider the following specific cases that illustrate this tension: a DaemonSet running a node-level log collector that legitimately needs hostPath volume mounts and elevated privileges; a development environment where resource limits cause more harm than good by triggering OOMKills during iterative testing; a legacy application that cannot run as a non-root user without container image changes; a Helm chart for a database that needs a writable filesystem but should otherwise be maximally hardened.

How should a code generator handle these cases? Analyze the following approaches: always generate the most secure configuration and let users override (maximally secure defaults, explicit opt-out); generate contextually appropriate configurations based on workload type annotations; generate insecure-but-functional configurations and emit warnings; generate multiple variants (production-hardened vs development-permissive).

Reason through the second-order effects: if a generator emits warnings for every security override, warning fatigue will cause users to ignore them all. If it silently accepts overrides, security regressions are invisible. What is the theoretically correct interaction model between a code generator and its security policy layer? Draw on analogies from compiler warning systems, linter configurations, and policy-as-code frameworks to develop a principled answer.
